Living in a 'city in a garden' like Singapore, we are blessed to have the privilege of urban life and being close to our natural environment at the same time. At Bukit Panjang in particular, residents are surrounded by it everyday! There's nature reserves, ponds, park connectors and canals that are part and parcel of life there.

On the PODSCAPE podcast, you can listen to residents reminiscing their encounters with nature and wildlife, and also hear ex-Bukit Panjang MP Dr @teo_ho_pin share his thoughts about the greenery in the neighbourhood! Listen to it on Spotify or through the link in our bio. 

If you are ready to spend a #Singapoliday in Bukit Panjang and be an explorer of the greens, we also suggest checking out @natureadventuressg, @naturesocietysingapore, @youngnautilus (and more) to discover more about Singapore's biodiversity. 🌱 🌸 🌺 🌷 💐 🍀 🌳 🐣

The Buddha Tooth Relic Temple is a remarkable 5-storey temple. When entering the gate, you’ll immediately notice the stunning main hall with its high ceiling. The bell tower and drum tower are on the same floor.⁠
The main draw is the solid gold 2-metre stupa on the 4th floor which is the place where the sacred relic is kept. Continuing up to the roof, there is a pagoda that has a large prayer wheel. The temple is built in a style based on the Buddhist mandala and integrated with the Buddhism of the Tang dynasty.⁠

Photo: Romeo A.

#babywearing before he gets too heavy for me..

We went kite flying at #punggolwaterwaypark ! We didn’t managed to do it during our #singapoliday so mama went to google and found a nearby spot. We decided to bring J1 to fly kite before she returns to school tomorrow.

I have never explored this part of the park. It’s interesting to find a small sand pit and a small water play area nearby (closed for now). We walked from #waterwaypoint towards #punggolsafra .

Watch how both Jack and J1 flew the kite! It wasn’t a windy day and thank God they managed to “catch” some wind!

We met a super friendly dog and went to have a little chat w his owner, @modernasianmother . She shared that she invites experts to share parenting tips on her fb live shows every Tuesday 9pm. Check it out if you are keen!

@instaphonetics I think the kite is from you?

“Singapoliday".
.
.

This is not a typo. 
Singapore launched a campaign to encourage Singaporean/SG residents to explore Singapore. Yes this is official !!! (Last pic) . 
First time I read it, I didn't notice but now I see "nine months". 
9 months ? 🙀.

9-month-campaign,,,, Is this hidden message like Singapore won't open the border till Mar-2021 ?.
.
.
ok, let's enjoy Singapore more. Not sure if Apple is cooperating with the campaign but Apple's got a pop-up mini-airport at the entrance. (pic 2) 😂🤣😅☺️😆😁😜 Yeah ~, it makes a "traveling" atmosphere. 
I believe Apple in your country also turned into a high-security mini-airport ?. The most powerful passport holder like me (Japanese passport 🇯🇵) still has to stand in a long line, though. 😍🤪🤩🥳😆😁.
.
.
Hopefully, weekly or monthly F-15SG fighter jets are included in "Singapoliday". Pic 3 is from Singapore National Day celebration. Singapore turned 55 years old this month. I think this could have been my first time to be in Singapore on National Day. It was sooooo quick and only 10 seconds that I could see but it was amazing. 
.
Pic 4: Parliament ,
Pic 5: #sgunited  Heartwarming Electronic Signage System, isn't it ?  I found it during lockdown. .
.
.
Oh yes, Pic 1 !  It is Changi Village. It is one of the natural beaches in Singapore 🇸🇬.

.
I have to consume paid off anyway. Hope more staycation places will be available later this year.

Chinatown⁠
⁠
Long before the arrival of Raffles in 1819, a small immigrant Chinese population had already settled in Singapore, cultivating gambier and pepper. When Singapore’s free port was established, more Chinese and other immigrants flocked to its shores. For easy administration, Raffles grouped various immigrant communities into ethnic quarters. In his 4 November 1822 letter to the Town Committee the area from the “Boat Quay southwest bank of the Singapore River” was designated a Chinese Kampong. This self-contained kampong or community settlement became the home of many Chinese immigrants, and a transit point for coolies (unskilled labourers) going to Malaya. That kampong and Chinese centre grew, eventually becoming Chinatown.⁠
⁠
The original kampong was divided into zones, a sector for each Chinese community of the same provincial origin and dialect group.⁠
⁠
Different trades were confined to specific areas, so each street took on its own identity. From delicacies to death-houses, there were businessmen, traders, craftsmen, hawkers and peddlers to provide all of the peoples’ needs. ⁠
⁠
Chinatown has become Singapore’s largest Historic District. Its four sub-districts – Bukit Pasoh, Kreta Ayer, Telok Ayer and Tanjong Pagar – were given conservation status in the late 1980s. Much of the town has changed, but fortunately, remnants of its colourful past are still present and old traditions have endured. During festivals such as the Lunar New Year, and the Mid-autumn Festival, there are celebrations and festive shopping. Always dressed for the occasion, Chinatown would be colourful, lit up and abuzz with activity, attracting not just the Chinese but other locals as well as tourists.⁠
⁠.⁠
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg⁠
⁠.⁠

Introducing to you another creature today! 

Premium High Gold Crossback Arowana is a natural colorant variant that originated from Bukit Merah Lake in Perak, Malaysia. 

The Cross Back Arowana is the most beautiful golden colour variant of the Asian Arowana.  And in the lake, different populations in the smaller tributaries have their own subtle differences compared to other populations. 

Like all Cross Back Arowana the gold rims on the scales reach only the 4th rows of scales when young but will spread towards the back until they reach the 6th level upon maturity. 

Thus, its name “Cross Back” means “Golden coloration crossing over the back”. The Full Gold Arowana has a gold based core and a gold rim on the outer edge. 

Good specimens will appear as a solid piece of gold when fully matured. Traits of a Full Gold Arowana are lighter color fins and eyes as compared to the other varieties of Cross Back Arowana. 

All Cross Back Gold Arowana are graded according to how fast the gold rims of the scales reach the 6th rows scales. 

Check out this Arowana as well as its accessories at Qian Hu Fish Gallery Singapore this weekend! For more information, please visit https://www.yihufish.com/visitors-info/retail-store/

Turned up for the session with our trusty portable mahjong table and was pleasantly surprised to see the girls all dressed in cheongsams, very fitting for our mahjong party. These two families have lived in Hong Kong for a while and the children were so eager to practise their Mandarin! Such a joy interacting with them! It was actually a birthday party for Mia (in red cheongsam) who turned 12 (apparently we also do kids parties now 😅) and so.. we were treated to a delicious apple pie cake baked by Mummy Alex. Mia's 9 year old sister Eden (in white cheongsam) was so good at the game that she was the one reminding others of the rules despite being the youngest. Looking forward to your mahjong birthday party, Eden! (Disclaimer: there were no more than 5 visitors to the household.)

Tomorrow night, 1st October, will be a full moon night. The moon will be at its roundest and biggest, also known as the Harvest Moon. It is also the Mid Autumn Mooncake festival.

Enjoy your moon photography tomorrow.

This photo of the moon was shot with a Sony G-Master 70-200mm lens. Shutter speed was set at 1/125, aperture at f/8 and ISO200.

post_caption:
Hotels in Singapore are now slowly opening up for staycations. But if that’s not your thing, there are still other activities you can do to feel like you’re on a holiday (or as close to one as you can get) – or as the Singapore Tourism Board calls it, a Singapoliday.
GO ISLAND-HOPPING
Island-hopping and taking a day trip to Singapore’s outer islands is one way to escape the bustle of city life. You can charter a yacht (if you can get groups to chip in) or check out ferry schedules. There’s Lazarus Island, St John’s Island, Pulau Jong, Pulau Ubin, among others – you can explore some of these and even have activities on the island or circle these at your leisure.
STAYCATIONS WITH BENEFITS
You can’t really get away from hotel staycations as an option – the plus side is there’s no hassle of dealing with an unfamiliar environment, currency or transport system. Some of these hotels have tied up with tour guides for special experiences. Let’s Go Tours for example does historic trails for guests of Raffles Hotel. Monster Day Tours is organising SG55 special edition tours, and working with hotels, such as Lyf Funan. 
BOOK YOUR OWN TOURS
Alternatively, you can go directly to the tour companies – Monster Day Tours, for example is running a “behind-the-scenes” tour of Changi Airport and Jewel, and Let’s Go Tours still does its bike tours if you reach out directly. 
Merchant associations will be working with the Society of Tourist Guides to develop heartland tours slated for September, STB has said. There will also be guidebooks via a Jalan Jalan: Your Good Hoods Guide initiative, to promote local neighbourhoods’ destinations.
ATTEND A WORKSHOP
Workshops are another great way to “escape” your routine at home. After all, when you’re overseas, people do take cooking classes right?
Schools such as Palate Sensations offer these. Or you might want some heritage-themed alternatives. One suggestion is the tea making and appreciation workshop at family-run Yixing Xuan Teahouse along Tanjong Pagar, after which you can explore the area. 
Read the story on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #staycation #Singapore #Singapoliday #hotels #travel #tourist #tours (Photo: Marcus Mark Ramos)

Happy National Day Everyone! Here's introducing to you Pufferfish such as Mbu pufferfish, which are commonly known as Giant Puffer or Giant Freshwater Puffer (Tetraodon Mbu) are chubby yet cute looking fish that are found worldwide. 
Mbu pufferfish are referred to as giant freshwater pufferfish due to their massive size. 
They have various interesting adaptations. They are one of the few fishes that can blink or close their eyes, attracting many fishkeepers over the years.
Additionally, they have peculiar and unique hunting techniques that are mesmerizing to watch.
They are renowned for their ability to puff up as a defense mechanism, a characteristic which they have evolved to protect themselves.
They can be a challenge to keep but they are very rewarding for fishkeepers, particularly experienced ones.
Join our telegram channel at https://t.me/qianhucorporation 
if you are interested to learn more about freshwater pufferfish such as Mbu pufferfish, including how to successfully care for them.
Once again, remember to check out these fishes as well as their accessories at Qian Hu Fish Gallery Singapore this weekend!

When I tell people I stay in Sembawang, the word ‘ulu’ comes to everyone’s mind immediately. I’ve been living here for almost a decade but I’ve never really checked out the surrounding attractions until recently when I started to re-explore this place. 𖠿𖤣   
   
In fact, Sembawang has a lot outdoor activities to offer for families! I especially love spending time in nature at the sandy beach. Look at my daughter Brielle and you will see how relax and calm she is when she’s at the beach. I love the gentle sea breeze, seeing my child’s sandy toes, hearing the sound of waves and gazing at the little creatures on the beach.    
     
Besides Sembawang, there are also many other attractions for families to enjoy as you take your #Singapoliday. I recently realised there are plenty of fun-filled activities for families to enjoy right here in the city. For example, one of them is the Kelong Tour. Since my son Brayden enjoys crab hunting a lot, I guess going on a fishing tour would interest him too!    
     
In case you didn’t know, SingapoRediscovers has a plethora of deals and promotions across attractions, dining, tours and more – currently ongoing: https://www.visitsingapore.com/singaporediscovers/singaporediscovers-promotions  
 
I can’t wait to rediscover the best of our local culture, nature, art, heritage and more! Remember to stay safe and adhere to safe distancing measures when you're out!

⁣
Singapoliday Series Part 4 -⁣
Haji Lane⁣
⁣
Ducky is at the front of a funky shop at Haji Lane in Singapore. Just next to Arab Street is a hipster enclave with shops, cafes and bars adorned with beautiful murals or selling interesting eclectic things. They are very colourful and have a very cool vibe to them. Before shisha was banned in 2016, this area (and Arab street) was where you could smoke this addictive fruity tobacco. ⁣
⁣
Just like Arab Street, the buildings are actually traditional two-storey heritage shophouses that are under government conservation. These shophouses can be converted to offices or retail with a new facade but the original architecture cannot be changed. In modern Singapore, these shophouses is a unique sight to the cityscape amidst the tall skyscrapers. ⁣
⁣
The last picture shows the scenery from our staycation hotel gym. You can see the Sultan Mosque among the houses with brick roofs which are shophouses. The tall buildings in the background are public housing flats where typical Singaporeans will stay in.⁣
⁣
By the way Ducky needs one of those  high waisted leggings to hide the muffin top from all that eating 😂😂😂.⁣
⁣
And we were surprised to find Sato-Chan, the elephant mascot typically found outside Japanese pharmacies being sold here. But... who pulled down Sato-Chan’s shorts?! 😱⁣
⁣

On this day as well, it was the first weekend in #phase2 where friends and gatherings of 5 were finally allowed after the initial lockdown so it was crazy crowded. We had a mini dumpling festival back then at my place as we didn't want to expose my mom to the potential virus at that point. Dumplings were meh (okay, pretty bad), but the wanton mee from Tanjong Rhu Wanton = great.

We later followed up that night with my favourite peanut tangyuan from Ah Balling at Bedok 85..and skipped that insane 1.5 hour queue for the famous bak chor mee (mind you, this was the first weekend of freedom+reopening after the renovation) so we tried the other famous BCM from Kaki Bukit 511 with a 20+ min wait! Unfortunately - Bedok 85 BCM wins.

You can also read more about my day here and all the places in Singapore which we visited + with more photos in this #WeekendswithMitsueki series ➡️ https://mitsueki.sg/2020/07/16/weekends-with-mitsueki-cb-phase-2-day-2-day-75-touristinsingapore-geylang-serai-x-city-plaza-x-katong-laksa-x-bedok-85-more-20-june-2020/

⁣
Singapoliday Series Part 5 -⁣
Rosti Breakfast at Marche⁣
⁣
Ducky is having a rosti breakfast set at Marche Movenpick restaurant ar Suntec City in Singapore. Our staycation hotel didn’t provide breakfast so we headed out to the nearby mall to get some lavish, holiday style breakfast instead of our usual bread and coffee. ⁣
⁣
We found a Marche at Suntec. Marche is a Swiss restaurant with a unique dining concept. You get a card when you enter the restaurant and is free to choose any table you like. Then you can go to the different cooking stations and your food is cooked to order. The order is then recorded in the card and tabulated when you pay the bill. You can get pastries, appetizers, main courses, salads and desserts. ⁣
⁣
The dish Marche is most famous for is their rosti. If you remember not too long ago the triplet ducks attempted making rosti (21 July post) and succeeded in burning it. We gotta learn some tips from the best and proceeded to observe how the Marche chef cooked their rosti. ⁣
⁣
First they used a crazy amount of oil per frying pan before putting the grated potatoes on it. There were at least 8 rosti in the row of frying pans cooking at one time. When it was time to turn the rosti, the chef deftly flipped the potato pancake in the air and it landed nicely on the other side. 😱😱😱 So skillful! The obscene amount of oil helped of course. It was difficult to keep an eye on 8 rosti cooking at the same time so sometimes when the chef checked on a particular rosti, found it too blackened or burnt, she just brought it to the bin and flipped the pan. 😱😱😱⁣
⁣
The rosti breakfast set ($16.90++) came with a fried egg, sausage, bacon and a dollop of sour cream. 🤤🤤 And the taste of the rosti - EXACTLY THE SAME as what we made! But then again if the ingredients of this dish is only oil and potatoes, the taste can’t be too different! ⁣
⁣
Is there Marche Movenpick in your country? ⁣
⁣

post_caption:
Warehouse
.
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

post_caption:
I've been escaping to Nature in the last couple of months, when I had lost interest in talking - to friends, on social media or messenging. How do I explain I've lost my voice, that I had nothing to say? A void existed where life was. Nature was a soothing balm, that one couldn't avoid. Blue skies 🌞. Beautiful clouds🌤️. Gorgeous sunrise 🌅 and sunsets 🌄. Birds 🐦 singing. And golden light.

It struck me that I had been most absorbed by lights during these dark times . The light of sunbeams radiating from the horizon. The golden light that precedes sunsets, bathing the world in a golden glow. MacRitchie has great golden lights bathing it when it's a beautiful very hot sunny day with great clouds. I was there that day. Remembering last time I saw golden lights when I escaped there after visiting my dying friend. I was shocked and upset. I could see she had less than a week left.

The last couple of weeks I've been reading about Thích Nhất Hạnh - a Vietnamese Thiền Buddhist monk, peace activist, and founder of the Plum Village Tradition. Just borrowed a few of his books but his quotes reached out to me in my silence.

"Calming allows us to rest, and resting is a precondition for healing." 
- Hanh Nhat Thich, The Heart of the Buddha's Teaching

.
.
.

Day 4 (and final day) of our Singapoliday was all about soaking up our final indulgences at the Ritz (champagne breakfast anyone?) till 4pm (late checkout ftw), zooming home in a cab for our favourite massage 💆‍♀️ and then heading back out to town to end our vacay with an omakase dinner! 🍣

I must say - cabbing home after a holiday (instead of having to go through airports and flights ✈️) felt really great! 😎

And with that, our little 4-day vacay came to an end (check out highlights above for everything we did). I highly recommend doing something like that for yourselves (it doesn’t even have to involve a hotel stay - like our day 1)! Just set aside X number of days where you are now allowed to do normal life stuff (work, errands, chores, normal workouts/tv shows) and take the time to try new activities/places instead. I promise you will come out of your break feeling recharged! ☀️☀️☀️

The humble, beloved and funny Ghib ojisan (@ghibli_ojisan).
Jade (@jadeseah), who we all had a crush on since we were kids.

Georgia (@thevintagevision), our cute and charming British expat.
Her partner and legendary veteran host Najip (@najipali).

Sweet Sherry (@sherrybyw) and her winsome enthusiasm.
Kelly (@kellylatimer), whose hosting skills are smooth as whiskey.

The journey has come to an end. 

We really enjoyed creating this mini-series with you, and we hope that you have enjoyed it as much as we did. 

The next time you're stuck indoors on a rainy weekend morning, and you start to miss us, come find us on IGTV. 

Until then, keep tagging us with your recommendations. Who knows, the rain and sun may align above to set the stage for our comeback 😉

🇸🇬𝗛𝗮𝗽𝗽𝘆 𝟱𝟱𝘁𝗵 𝗯𝗶𝗿𝘁𝗵𝗱𝗮𝘆 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗮𝗽𝗼𝗿𝗲!🇸🇬⁣
⁣
Today is our nation's birthday, and on this special occasion, I would like to share with you why I love Singapore. But if you are tired of reading things that share how great Singapore’s Changi Airport ✈️ is, or how clean and green it is, here are 3 other reasons!
⁣
❤️ Blessed to be a Muslim 🧕 in Singapore ⁣
A lot of halal food everywhere (although I sometimes complain there are a lottttt of coffee shops without halal food oops). Here we also have 68 mosques and we can usually drop by anytime it is open. The mosques 🕌 are clean, well-run and you can even find a number of musollahs around the country with a quick Google search. Alhamdulillah!😍😍⁣
⁣
❤️ There will always be shops opened till a reasonable time, 365 days a year⁣
Mustafa Centre (a shopping mall) is open 24 hours. Yep, a 24 hours mall🛍️. On Sundays, I struggle even to find an open supermarket in some parts of Europe on a Sunday during layovers. 😧⁣
⁣
❤️ The most powerful passport in the world🛂 ⁣
Sometimes we lose to Japan and Germany, but that’s just a part of life. 🤣 (I'm just joking)

This Japanese bar tucked in National Gallery actually managed to make a cocktail into a Beauty & the Beast jar along with the blue light and live stardust performance. This “Confession” drink is more magical than gimmicky though rather pricey at $34++. Base of alcohol is a premium Japanese wine which tastes pretty good and a delicate small edible rose airflown from Japan and nothing like I’ve seen before. Food’s pretty decent too. Just remember to reserve way in advance.

Legend has it that a turtle saved a group of sailors from drowning by transforming itself into an island during the ninth lunar month. That island is now known as Kusu Island (kusu means tortoise or turtle in Hokkien) and has became a place of worship in Singapore.

Home to a Chinese temple and three Malay shrines, Kusu Island draws thousands of devotees each year during the pilgrimage season. These pilgrims would pay homage to deities and saints of different races and religions, such as Tua Pek Gong (Merchant God) and Syed Abdul Rahman, as they seek good fortune and health. 

Today, the tranquil beaches and lagoons make Kusu Island an attractive day-trip destination for both tourists and locals alike.

Hear more about Kusu Island in this interview with Mr Lee Liang Hye who worships at the island: http://bit.ly/NASKusuIsland (link in bio)

.
Holiday vibes in my own country! It’s been a while since I've visited the beach. This one was taken at Palawan Beach in Sentosa. I didn't appreciate it when I was young, and thought that it was just a typical beach.
.
As I revisit the beach again, I found some hidden gems. Something I hadn't noticed before. I was intrigued by how these particular trees were neatly arranged. They caught my attention and I immediately asked @yaisyusman to pose for the shot. Bonus: I managed to capture the kids playing around too!
.
At times, we tend to be ungrateful for the things we have. Little do we know that we have to open our eyes and appreciate the beauty around us. The things close to us are indeed worth rediscovering.
.
Check out @stb_sg’s Instagram stories to find out what other hidden gems @yaisyusman and I discovered as part of the #SingapoRediscovers campaign!
.
#Singapore #Sentosa #PassionMadePossible
So we were on a mission to find the best shoes to go our trip and we found Ted’s #airjordan1. With it’s fresh hues, and clean lines, it’s a classic, remade!

I think like @lola.thewonderweenie mentioned, we are an attraction by ourselves. We attract more crowd’s attention than those funny looking super trees there. I think we should be called DOXIES BY THE BAY. 🤪
.

post_caption:
Last but not least we would like to introduce to you our Golden Cobra Snakehead (Channa aurantimaculata) also known as the Orange-spotted snakehead! It is a species of Channidae originated from India.

They earn their name because their flattened shape and the scales on their heads are reminiscent of the large epidermal scales on snakes.

The moderate size and brilliant coloration has quickly made this species a popular specimen within the aquarium hobby. 

They have also been thrust into the limelight because of the picture painted of them as an aquatic invasive species but overall, snakeheads make great aquarium fish if given proper care.

Join our telegram channel at https://t.me/qianhucorporation 
to learn everything you need to know about this Channa Cobra!
 
Head to Qian Hu Fish Gallery Singapore this weekend to check out these creatures as well as their accessories! For more information, please visit https://www.yihufish.com/visitors-info/retail-store/

Guess the fish! 🐠🐟

Indigenous to the lower Amazon region, primarily the Parnaíba River of Brazil, this mystery fish is found in flooded forest regions as well as in creeks and small tributaries. This fish typically is smaller and more stout in build. It has a shorter head and rounded snout. Also, it has a silvery gray body. Furthermore, a dark zigzag stripe runs along the lateral line from its gill to its tail. Above and below this dark line is a section that is not spotted, beyond which are many small, isolated black spots of varying size. 

Additionally, its dorsal fin is transparent with a large black blotch on the upper fin that does not extend down into the body. The caudal fin has vertical rows of dark brown spots that gives the appearance of striping. The anal, adipose, pectoral, and ventral fin also has these spots, but it is much paler in colour than on the caudal fin. Instead of scales, this fish has overlapping hard plates, known as scutes.
Overall, this fish can reach an adult size of slightly over 2 inches.

Stay tuned as the answer will be revealed tomorrow!

I had the pleasure of dialing in from our #Singapoliday at Raffles Hotel Singapore to be part of the regional #AHICE2020 conference, hosted from Sydney.

What made this conference so special?

It gave us all the optimism that it could be done. With enough pivoting, and a healthy amount of resilience, 2020 doesn't have to cancel everything.

Well. Done. James Gregory Wilkinson & Hotel Management Magazine (HM)

Originally scheduled for May 5th in Melbourne. Flights booked, presentation prepared, however many variables out of our control.

A new date for September confirmed. Flights booked optimistically. A second wave inspires a pivot to Sydney as a hybrid event.

Record numbers, interactivity, high-quality content for the archives & a live international audience and panel.
Great success.

While we wait for business travel to return, this proves that in the middle of a pandemic, we are still able to create highly effective events that bring us all together.

Originally billed for the Appetite F&B session, brain-child of the charismatic Michael Rodrigues, I spoke on how applying a #systemsthinking mindset to #supplychain can allow us to be more agile, give better & more local guest experiences and drive a dramatic positive environmental impact.

#Accor #livelimitless

📸

Heritage buildings and kampung (village) scenes around Aliwal Street.
.
#exploresingapore #jalanjalan #localtourist #singapoliday #heritage #kampung

⁣
Singapoliday Series Part 2 -⁣
Arab Street⁣
⁣
Ducky is at Masjid Sultan or Sultan Mosque at the Arab Street area in Singapore. ⁣
⁣
Across the road from our staycation hotel was the culture rich district of Kampung Glam where Arab Street is located. The whole area is Islamic and Middle Eastern-centric and have a collection of shops selling bales of cloth for sewing Muslim clothing,  Turkish lamps, carpets and more. Most of the restaurants here are halal certified, even the ones selling Sichuan Mala cuisine and Japanese ramen. You can also find Malay, Turkish and Lebanese restaurants and eateries in the area. ⁣
⁣
In the heart of this area is the Sultan Mosque. The mosque was built in 1824 for Sultan Hussein Shah, the First Sultan of Singapore. We didn’t go in (I don’t think we can anyway as places of worship are closed unless you are a worshipper who registered beforehand) so we just admired the building from the outside. ⁣
⁣
Walking through the back lanes, we found many artistic murals on the walls. The area was not just rich in culture but artistic too. ⁣
⁣
Finally we walked past a perfume shop selling oudh. It smelt really good even from a distance. It was nothing like what we have smelt before. Later we found out that oudh is also known as agarwood and is a fragrant dark wood used in incense and perfume. When the wood is infected by a particular type of mold, it reacts by producing a dark scented resin in which the oil is distilled from it. It is very rare and oudh oil can sell for US$30,000 per kilogram 😱. Wow. ⁣
⁣
Have you smelled oudh before? ⁣
⁣

post_caption:
We think the kiddos are ready for more adventures after our recent cycling session at #eastcoastpark and long walk at #changijurassicmile . So, we took them “overseas” to Pulau Ubin.

We went to #changivillageferryterminal to take a bumboat to Pulau Ubin. We had to queue up and wait for the bumboat uncle to gather the people for each ride. We paid $4 per pax including J2 and took about 15 mins to reach. J1 was initially very scare to get on the boat but it turned out to be the most enjoyable time for her.

We rented 2 bicycles with child seats after we reached. There are a few bicycle rental shops so you can slowly take your pick. It costed us $40 for 2 bikes and we get to use it for the whole day (we were only there for half a day). Thankfully, the lady accepted paylah.

We cycled to Chek Jawa Wetlands. The journey was fun with many beautiful sceneries. There are a few steep slopes and I had to push the bicycle up the slopes with J2 sitting on it.

Bicycles are not allowed in Chek Jawa so we parked ours at the entrance like the others. No locks are provided for the bikes. 

We were greeted by the wild boars at the entrance! After which, we spotted monitor lizard, crabs and mudskipper! We also saw some monkeys on our way to Chek Jawa.

Poor J1 had a fall towards the end of the walk and suffered a few scratches. J2 was so tired that he dozed off on the child seat while I cycled back to Jetty.

We had our lunch at the zhi char stall. The pig’s leg noodles reminded us of our childhood.. 😆😆 We wanted to try the “famous” coconut ice cream but it was closed.

It was a lovely adventure for us and we will definitely be back for more! Thank God for the beautiful weather (Forecast stated 60% chance of rain)

Some tips if you are planning to go:

- Bring more cash as there are no ATMs
- Bring enough water (I didn’t see any water coolers around. There is one drink stall along the way to Chek Jawa)
- Bring snacks for the kiddos
- Mosquito repellent 
- sunscreen
- Put on long pants for kiddos

⁣
Singapoliday Series Part 6 -⁣
The Singapore Nightscape⁣
⁣
Ducky took a walk along the Esplanade. The weather was fine and there were many couples seated by the steps, with appropriate distancing of course. This is the first time we have been here since the lockdown and the night scenery of the city is still as beautiful. ⁣
⁣
We started from the Esplanade and could see Fullerton Hotel on the right and the iconic Marina Bay Sands, Art Science Museum and the Helix Bridge lit up in red. Further back was the Singapore Flyer, a big Ferris wheel kinda like the London Eye. ⁣
⁣
Inside Marina Bay Sands, we saw the Digital Light Canvas - an artwork by Team Lab from Japan. It looks like a fountain but they are all just lights and lasers. This used to be a skating rink that does not use ice but plastic instead. We have not seen any one skating inside before - no wonder it closed down. 😂 This light installation is a much better use of the space! ⁣
⁣

Besides a thriving cafe scene and abundance of shopping malls, did you know that Singapore also has amazing nature spots🍂and hiking trails?

𝑯𝒐𝒘 𝒕𝒐 𝒈𝒐 𝒕𝒐 𝑪𝒐𝒏𝒆𝒚 𝑰𝒔𝒍𝒂𝒏𝒅:
My friend and I had a hard time finding the place but this is a way easier route! Take bus 84🚌 from Punggol interchange and alight at Punggol Rd End bus stop. If you know of an accessible route, do share with me please.

Exploring Suburban Singapore is one of my virtual photography series conducted through zoom session for an hour.

Bringing you on the new normal of travel and discovery while international travel to location is still not possible.

Turning a year older in Sentosa this year. Alhamdulillah for everything that have happened in my life this year, the amazing things and the dissapontment, the good and the bad, I take it as a great blessings from HIM.

Idk what to put for my caption actually but still I want to upload these photos so that it will be on my feed... 

The recent birthday trip, though it supposed to be like my birthday celebration... but to me its more like a close family bonding time between me with my kids and also my husband. 

Thank u to family and friends for all the well wishes and prayers... May Allah grant the same for everyone too... 😍

#family #familyiseverything #husbandandwife #staycation #singapoliday

Palm trees, clear skies, and shallow waters (that we can walk to the neighbouring islands)... can you guess where this picture is taken? Make a guess and leave us a comment! #sailingholidayinsg #secretparadise #ximulasail #singapoliday #singaporediscovers

Ducky is outside a very interesting building shaped like a camera. This is the Vintage Camera Museum in Singapore which showcases all sort of cameras, from spy cams to huge 6 metre ones. However they were closed when we went there. Maybe next time! 

The museum was located just a short walk from the Sultan Mosque which we featured during our staycation in the Arab Street area. We loved the vibes there and so returned again to see more of the unexplored sights. 

Along North Bridge Road were shophouses with many halal food establishments, including a pasta place and dim sum place with long queues. We also walked past Hotel Nuve, a budget hotel with beautiful wall murals. The sky was blue that evening and the Sultan Mosque, adorned with Singapore flags for national day looked really pretty against the blue sky. 

Finally we found some cute plush ducks waiting to be rescued at the nearby mall. 😍

Singapore's amazing Supertrees and the mid-autumn festival (which ended last week)! 🌲🌲
.

The queue to enter the Apricot Grove was insanely long that night, so we just viewed from the back. Does anyone know what song is that playing in the background at the supertree grove?
.

And wow, these trees actually do more than just look nice. Some of these supertrees are installed with photovoltaic cells to provide the energy for lighting up the trees and some function as exhaust vents for the two conservatories! Amazing!
.

.
Back here at FIT @wsingapore after a few months (we were here just before #circuitbreaker) and looking back at my old video, I was much pudgier, less lean and probably weaker then too

.

post_caption:
Ducky is bringing some awesome fusion cakes to #honeygroveteapartytuesday today - kueh salat and chocolate snickers flavour!⁣
⁣
In the Arab Street area, besides having many halal eateries selling Malay food, Turkish or Lebanese food, there are also many shops selling traditional cakes, western pastries and cakes. All these cake shops are halal certified and suitable for our Muslim friends. The shops are small and packed with beautiful mouth-watering kueh (those traditional cakes that the triplet ducks tried to make), meringues, cakes, pastries and cookies. ⁣
⁣
Due to the small shop size and the current social distancing measures in place, the shops are required to put the maximum number of customers allowed in the shop on a notice at their door (usually only 3-4 customers). This can result in a long queue (1 meter apart of course) outside the shop. But as you know, long queues mean good food. After scanning the QR code to register your attendance for contact tracing, you can go in. ⁣
⁣
We chanced upon this fusion cake shop called Julie Bakes. They sell normal cakes like salted caramel and peppermint chocolate, and they also sell really interesting fusion cakes, merging traditional with modern. We were particularly attracted to ‘putri salat’ which is another name for kueh salat which the triplets made recently. The actual traditional kueh is a layer of pandan custard with a layer of glutinous rice. But glutinous rice in a western style cake? #ShutUpAndTakeMyMoney⁣
⁣
The cakes are generally $8 or $8.50 per slice, much pricier than the usual slices at a cafe but omg these cakes are like six storeys tall. Totally worth the higher price.⁣
⁣
The verdict? The kueh salat cake tastes so good! 🤤🤤🤤 The glutinous rice inside was well balanced and didn’t feel too heavy, and the pandan sponge cake was fragrant and a delight to eat. We want to try ondeh ondeh next, and putu piring...⁣
⁣
The last picture shows how the actual traditional kueh salat looks like, which we tried to make. ⁣
⁣

Was feeling a little bad recently for slipping up again on things I really ought to do (and some not), being distracted by things that kinda ought not to matter. I know we always say that what's done can't be undone and that we should just move on and learn from mistakes, but what if we don't learn, and still make the same ones over and over again? That becomes a problem, doesn't it? I guess the important thing is to never stop trying though, even when we keep failing, even when things get difficult, even when we are tired to the bone. Rest yes, but don't stop learning, growing, experiencing and feeling - I think, that's when we stop living.

📷: @martinetalexandra

post_caption:
Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on. 

Highlighting a few artworks

🅰 🆃🅰🅱🅻🅴 🆆🅷🅴🆁🅴 🅻🅸🆃🆃🅻🅴 🅿🅴🅾🅿🅻🅴 🅻🅸🆅🅴
The little people will jump onto your hand or object you place on the table. Check out the pan where you can cook an egg. 😁 This is just cute to the max!

🅻🅸🅶🅷🆃 🅱🅰🅻🅻 🅾🆁🅲🅷🅴🆂🆃🆁🅰
Push, bounce and roll the lighted balls to create your own orchestra! The kids couldn't stop running about to push the balls and watch them change colours. Too fun!

🆂🅺🅴🆃🅲🅷 🆃🅾🆆🅽
Watch your artwork ( buildings or vehicles) come to life on the big screen here. Just grab the paper and crayons provided and colour away. After scanning them, they appear on the screen and vehicles start to move around. It's amazing to see your creations come to life. 

Check out our IG TV for more! 

It was a well spent afternoon with family and we hope to go there and have another round of fun soon! 😁

This pandemic has certainly changed the way we dress, shop and spend. The fashion industry is also undergoing a long overdue metamorphosis, and it’ll be interesting to see which brands will evolve with its consumers’ changing preferences and stay relevant - tweaking the way they source, design and sell. With many of us still working from home, resort-style wear and light clothings that we can wear both at home and out, seem to be the rising trends. What are you wearing these days? More flowy dresses perhaps, jeans & t-shirts or athleisure wear ? Feeling breezy and carefree in a safari dress that makes me feel like I’m on a #Singapoliday☀️ while indulging in a little colonial nostalgia at the newly refurbished @raffleshotelsingapore.

Did you know that there are a whopping 90 skyscrapers in our little red dot?⠀
⠀
Interestingly though, in Singapore, it is forbidden to build buildings higher than 280 meters. ⠀
⠀
The tallest skyscraper though stands at 290m, like a proud rebel, flouting this rule (ok..ok..they sought a special permission from the Urban Redevelopment Authority)⠀
⠀
The latest addition to this already-impressive skyline chooses to wow us with it’s shape rather than it’s height. A shiny rounded glass dome that floats on the Singapore river. They say it’s design was inspired by the Pantheon in Rome. A Roman temple inspiring the new-age temple of the Gen Z ,aka, the Apple Showroom. Rather apt.⠀
⠀
There she stands, sun-bathing, acting as a mirror for the skyline..⠀
⠀
You wonder, “Is this what they mean by reflected glory?” :P⠀
.
.⠀
D&I spent an entire morning shooting with this beautiful backdrop! It was our first photoshoot in almost 6 months and we had an absolute ball. Are you guys having fun exploring your home cities as well?

I seriously think Bray's a rural boy trapped in a city! ⁣
⁣
Thanks to award-winning tour agency @letsgotoursingapore, I got to verify this in a morning at Kampong Lorong Buangkok, for a cosy and interactive 《𝐀 𝐋𝐨𝐧𝐠 𝐋𝐨𝐧𝐠 𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐀𝐠𝐨: 𝐕𝐢𝐥𝐥𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬 𝐭𝐨 𝐇𝐢𝐠𝐡 𝐑𝐢𝐬𝐞𝐬》tour. This curated guided tour is from a NEW LAUNCH of the 'This is Home' Local Edu-Tainment Tour series, part of 10 exciting, educational, immersive and experiential walking tours to encourage locals to rediscover Singapore, explore our local culture and heritage, nature, art, and architecture and more! ⁣
⁣
When we started in the morning, our friendly guide, Yap, asked Bray if he would like to stay in a Kampong. He hesitated and replied meekly, "No...Because very muddy!" However, in less than an hour into the tour, he was so mesmerised spotting millipedes to poke (🙈😝) and declared that he would love to stay here anytime! ⁣
⁣
What else did he say and we do?⁣
It was so fun that I'd to blog about it!⁣
Check it out k! #linkinbio too!⁣
👉 https://belandbray.wordpress.com/2020/09/10/letsgotour-kampong-experience/⁣
⁣
Look out for more immersive and experiential walking tours by @letsgotoursingapore!⁣
Suitable for families with children, students, couples, and small groups of friends, their curated tours will be great bonding activities for the weekends or school holidays. Singaporeans will also be able to utilise their #SingapoRediscovers Vouchers (tourism credits) on these tours!⁣
⁣
Thank you @letsgotoursingapore & @atmcbizexpert again for the awesome #mediainvite. The lovely Kampong tour is really one-of-its-kind! ⁣

🇸🇬: With the inability to travel out of Singapore these days. We decided to have ourselves a little Singapoliday!

The Fullerton Hotel Singapore is the current ranked 1 hotel on TripAdvisor. And when a GREAT credit card deal came up (now expired), I knew I had to give this place a go. 

A fantastic room, which definitely deserves a 5 star rating. Room had everything you'd want (and need). A massive tub! Which is important for staycays imo. And a nespresso coffee machine (to just get that atas feel y'know?)

With the credit card deal, we also had $80 dining credit and breakfast for 2! Reviews will be up over the next 2 posts! 

Do like and give me a follow for tips on how to make the most of Hotel Breakfast Buffets during Phase 2!

My 500 th post on Instagram - Celebrating 5 Years in Singapore.

First of all, Happy Birthday Singapore. You have given us such warmth and love.

This day marks the day we landed in Singapore to start our journey here. It has been a great 5 years - Anokhi came into our lives and she was born here. We have made some lovely friends here irrespective of the Races and we live in a great community. We have had some amazing local cuisines and been to lovely places inside the island.

I thank God for all the good things in our life and thank you my Instafamily for all the support and love. I promise to keep producing more helpful content.

Cheers❤️

It's another long weekend! Our singapoliday continued to wetlands today - then off to the famous bollywood veggies for lunch (we were famished by noon!) 🥰

Sightings Summary 
1) Estuarine Croc (more known as salt water croc, one of the largest species in the world, we spotted a smaller one 🐊 sunbathing)
2) Saint Andrew's cross spider 🕷🕸
3) Mudskipper (blue spotted in the pic, & yellow spotted)🐟
4) Malayan water monitor (aplenty) 😂🦎
5) the beautiful White bellied sea eagle 🦅
6) plenty of great egret and a blue heron 🐦
7) a few blue-eared king fisher that were too fast in action before we can snap 📸 them 

By the end of the day i could still hear the cicadas 'singing' around my ears 😂 anyway a great 43km ride and 4km exploration by foot! The pit viper was too hard to spot with all the greens, we will be back for you... 🐍🤣😂

#singapoliday#wetlands#discovery#crocodile#monitorlizard#exploration#cycleday#bollywoodveggies#yummyfood#cycletoeatmore

As promised, here's more of our outing to @jurongbirdpark.sg ! We started off at Penguin Coast and saw so many cute penguins swimming in the water or just standing around! But it was too crowded for our comfort so we didn't stay for too long. I guess it's popular because you are talking about irresistible penguins and the place is air-conditioned.

Next up we decided to take the tram to go one round around the park and made a pit stop to look at beautiful pigeons and other birds at one of the open concept enclosures. We could go up close to take a look as some of them were just roaming around freely. There were so many of them and of different sizes and colours. It got everyone all excited!

We wanted to catch the High Flyers show but sadly, it was full half an hour before the show commenced. We saw people queuing up way before the show started and I guess with limited capacity, you just have to queue up very early and wait for the show to start. 

Anyway we continued to explore the rest of the park. It was really relaxing as we walked and took the tram at times. Our favourite area is the African Treetops because there are so many cute colourful birds there and a hanging bridge. You also cannot miss making a pit stop at the Waterfall Aviary for a glimpse of the waterfall when you go to the Jurong Bird Park.

Take an easy 2hr stroll through a coastal trail and Singapore’s only protected mangrove forest and come face to face with wild saltwater crocs 🐊, snakes 🐍, migratory shorebirds (Sep to March) and majestic hornbills. You will also surely be greeted with gigantic monitor lizards 🦎 crossing your path now and then. 

There are plenty of wildlife professional photographers around who can provide good tips but it’s best to bring your own binoculars to really be able to enjoy the birds which come to roost and find food. #sglgexperience #sungeibuloh #sungeibulohwetlandreserve

Introducing to you another fish called Bristol Shubunkin! 

The Bristol Shubunkin was developed in the United Kingdom. The ancestral fish are believed to be a mixture of the Japanese Shubunkin and a black Moor or Demekin. Two variations exist today such as the heart shaped tail, often referred to as the Classic Bristol and the B shaped tail commonly known as the Modern Bristol.

Remember to check out this fish at Qian Hu Fish Gallery Singapore this weekend too!

This evening’s National Day’s fireworks in the heartland of Singapore.

Filmed this from the rooftop and took some shots in between.

Some tips about fireworks photography:-

1. Watch your composition. Fireworks  usually explode higher than your estimated framing. 
2. Shoot as much as possible at the start of the firework because smoke will build up and the sky will be filled with smoke. You will have hard time “dehazing” your photo in post. Example in the last photo (swipe to your left).

#singapoliday Day 2

Yes! We went to the Zoo!! Did you get it right?

A snippet of our day made into a video. Best watched with sound on..

Some things to note if you are planning to go zoo anytime soon..

1. Book your tickets early
2. Remember to book token feeding and tram tickets together with your tickets
3. Forget about the animals shows. (They are limiting to 50 pax per show and it’s already full half an hour before show time!)

We booked the tickets before checking weather forecast. The forecast said thundery showers over many areas in the late mornings. We prepared J1 for it and prayed together for good weather.

God really sayang J1 and gave us a terrific weather! Cloudy and cooling weather. It rained when the kids were napping and stopped when they woke! It’s drizzled a little when we were queuing to feed the giraffe but stopped when it was our turn.

Thank God for wonderful weather!

Guess where we are going tomorrow!

post_caption:
🇸🇬: Dinner at The Courtyard in Fullerton Hotel Singapore. 

Chicken Caesar Salad: Finally! A proper caesar salad! Dressing didnt taste like those bottled ones. Chicken was nice a tender. Croutons were homemade (big and garlicky!) And they had real anchovies! Which, imo... is a must have on any caesar salad!

The Fullerton Burger: A chunky thicc prime beef patty. Juicy and tender on the inside done perfectly medium. Sweet caramelized onions. Crispy salty bacon. Served with a side of salad and chips. This was a great burger! So much so that the lady wanted more of it and I had to eat hers :(

Braised Beef Cheek: This was a massive piece of beef! Tender and flavourful. Even the tendons had become more or less melt in your mouth. Served on top of a potato mash and with stir fried greens. With a great sauce (black pepper mushroom jus). 

Service: 10/10. Not sure if because we were one of 5 tables that night (it was a tuesday) but service was fantastic. We even got a chocolate cake to finish!

Food: 9/10. Missing that 1 because if we paid full price, it'd be on the higher side. But still, to be expected when dining at Singapores top hotel

Ambience: 10/10. Space was huge, set in the history of the general post office. Simply great. 

Breakfast review tomorrow! *will be coming with tips on how to maximise your breakfast during phase 2!

For a taste of HK 🇭🇰, @joy_luck_teahouse brings you 3 iconic edibles - egg tart, pineapple polo bun, and HK milk tea. If you want to hunt down the pastry skin egg tart, come early as it gets sold out by 2pm. The butter cookie crust might be a tad too thick for some, and best eaten warm out of the oven. 

I would actually buy the milk tea again as a substitute for bubble tea if I can get it without queuing together with the rest in line. Two outlets for you to choose from: ION orchard and Bugis Junction. Swipe right for menu. Queue is about 30mins on the average.

Singapoliday Series Part 1 - ⁣
Prawn Noodles & Ngoh Hiang⁣
⁣
Ducky is having prawn noodles and ngoh hiang at Blanco Court Prawn Mee at Beach Road in Singapore.⁣
⁣
As you know, nobody can travel or fly for leisure out of Singapore, no thanks to the coronavirus. The government has encouraged us to take a ‘singapoliday’ or holiday in Singapore instead, visiting local attractions and having staycations, which is what we did!⁣
⁣
We did a 2D1N stay at Pan Pacific Serviced Residences at Beach Road which was located across the culture rich district of Kampung Glam. It also overlooks Marina Bay and we could see the Singapore Flyer and the Formula One area. ⁣
⁣
After checking in we went to the famous prawn noodle shop across the road. The soup broth was boiled for many hours with the prawns and is so thick and flavourful. Only grouse was that the portion of noodles are too small (remember ducky had a voracious appetite). ⁣
⁣
In the same eatery was a ngoh hiang stall. Ngoh hiang is a dish where you get to pick what you want, mainly lots of deep fried stuff like prawn crackers, fried fritters, fried rolls, century egg and other fried, unhealthy oily stuff 😂(lovely, just how we like it. 😋#EatFirstWorryLater) The chosen items are then cut up and eaten with a sweet sauce. ⁣
⁣
Back at the hotel we visited the swimming pool but the weather was crappy so we went to the gym and ran 3km to work out the oily fried ngoh hiang 🤤🤤🤤 we had earlier. ⁣
⁣
More to come...⁣
⁣

Masjid Sultan Mosque⁠
Surrounded by rows of shophouses Masjid Sultan Mosque stands out with its massive golden domes and huge prayer hall, it is one of the must-see sites if you’re in the historic Kampong Gelam district. ⁠
The mosque has a long history that goes back to 1824 when it was built for Sultan Hussein Shah, the first Sultan of Singapore. It has since passed through many development stages before becoming what it is today. ⁠
While you’re there, check out the onion-shaped domes as each dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute. ⁠
In 1975, the mosque was gazetted as a national monument, it has been a focal point for the Muslim Community. ⁠
To find out more about the mosque, click on the link http://sultanmosque.sg/about-us/sultan-mosque-history⁠

Thinking of where to go for a staycation? As of Jul 28, you’ve got 139 STB-approved hotels to choose from. Here’s our curated list of the most enticing deals.

FOR COUPLES: Raffles Hotel’s Suite Life Staycation package (from S$795++). Aside from enjoying the hotel’s amenities (with a Singapore Sling in hand), it comes comes with S$100 nett experiential credit to be used at Raffles-operated restaurants and bars, Raffles Spa and the Raffles Boutique.

FOR FAMILIES: Shangri-La’s Family Fun Playcation package (from S$378++), where kids can enjoy the Splash Zone, Singapore’s largest outdoor water playground and family pool in a luxury hotel, with six water play areas including 2.6 m-high slides.  

FOR PET OWNERS: InterContinental Singapore’s Pawfect Staycation package (from S$350++) means your four-legged friends get their own welcome amenity basket, plush pet bed, gourmet treats and an exclusive pet-friendly menu. Humans get treated too, of course. 

FOR NATURE LOVERS: Sofitel Sentosa Resort & Spa’s Retreat to Sanctuary package (from S$388++) let’s you enjoy the property’s greenery (with cameos from resident peackocks). There’s a one-hour massage and a fish spa experience thrown in.

FOR TECH GEEKS: Yotel’s Robo-cation package (from S$195++) features crewbots Yolanda and Yoshi catering to your needs and will send amenities and refreshments to your room.

FOR FOODIES: Goodwood Park Hotel’s Restless In Singapore package (from S$498++) lets you indulge in good food for two nights, from three-course lunches and dinners to afternoon tea.

FOR DESIGN LOVERS: Hotel Soloha’s Say Hello to Staycations package (from S$158++) is an option if you want to stay at a well-designed boutique hotel in a restored heritage building at Keong Saik neighbourhood.

FOR HEALTHCARE HEROES: Mandarin Oriental’s Celebrating Healthcare Heroes package (from S$288++) rewards healthcare workers with a host of (well-deserved) tailoured privileges to relax from all the much-appreciated hard work.

For more details, read the story on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #Singapore #staycation #Singapoliday #hotels (Photo: InterContinental Singapore)

Have you gotten it right? 😆😜

The answer is Leopard Corydoras, which is commonly known as Corydoras julii! Great job to those who guessed correctly! For the rest of us, nice try! Let’s all try harder again in the next round! 

Corydoras julii is not demanding and tolerates a range of initial water parameters. Water can be slightly acidic to slightly alkaline, with soft to medium-hard water hardness. The substrate in this fish’s tank must be soft, as it will scavenge the bottom for bits of food. Sand or small and smooth gravel is suitable. Driftwood is recommended, as well as other items that can serve as hiding places. Plants are also essential. Floating plants are often used to dim the lighting, as this fish does not appreciate bright lights.

Furthermore, Corydoras julii accepts most food. You can offer it sinking tablets or pellets as their primary diet. Live foods like brine shrimp, daphnia, and bloodworms can be offered to supplement their diet. Because it is a nocturnal, it is best to feed it before lights are turned off.

Lastly, Corydoras julii is best kept in a school of a minimum of four or more. It gets along well with small catfish and small peaceful fish. Possible tankmates include small members of the tetra family, rasboras, dwarf cichlids, danios and other small community fish. You should avoid any large or aggressive fish.

Happy National Day to Everyone once again! Today we would like to introduce to you our Vampire Crab species! These include Mandarin Vampire Crabs, Halloween Vampire Crabs, Rainbow Vampire Crabs, Tomato Vampire Crabs, Golden Eye Vampire Crabs and Red Arm Vampire Crabs. 

When everyone thinks of pretty-looking species that nature has to offer, crabs are often not the first creature to come to our mind. However, one look at these stunning vampire crabs is bound to change your mind. 
These crabs' blazing eyes and spectacular colours have attracted many aquarists over the years. 

Are you planning to own one or do you currently own one? 

This species has a unique set of care requirements that many potential and existing owners are not well-prepared for. 

Do not worry, we have got you covered!

Join our telegram channel at https://t.me/qianhucorporation 
to learn everything you need to know about Vampire Crab care.
 
Once again, check out these Vampire Crabs as well as their accessories at Qian Hu Fish Gallery Singapore this weekend! For more information, please visit https://www.yihufish.com/visitors-info/retail-store/

𝐋𝐢𝐤𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐭𝐚𝐤𝐞 𝐩𝐡𝐨𝐭𝐨𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐟𝐨𝐨𝐝, 𝐭𝐫𝐚𝐯𝐞𝐥, 𝐬𝐞𝐥𝐟𝐢𝐞, 𝐰𝐞𝐟𝐢𝐞, 𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐞𝐨 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐞𝐭𝐜. 𝐁𝐔𝐓 𝐜𝐚𝐧’𝐭 𝐠𝐞𝐭 𝐢𝐭 𝐫𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐨𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧, 𝐞𝐝𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 & 𝐞𝐭𝐜 ?

post_caption:
Central Fire Station
⁠
The Central Fire Station (CFS), also known as the Hill Street Fire Station, is Singapore’s oldest surviving fire station. Completed in 1909, the distinctive red-and-white brick building was gazetted as a national monument by the Preservation of Monuments Board in recognition of its significance in Singapore’s history. The Singapore Civil Defence force subsequently embarked on conservation and reconstruction work, including building the Heritage Gallery to commemorate the contributions and rich history of the local fire service and its firemen. The gallery is located in the oldest part of the station, and features photographs of major fires, old firefighting equipment and uniforms, interactive displays, and audio-visual presentations to engage the public. Its highlights include a 19th-century fire engine, and the 30-metre lookout tower that visitors can climb up.⁠
.⁠
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg⁠
Photo: Choo Yut Shing⁠

:: I am obsessed with an uber clean room with minimal rubbish in the bin (yes, I'm that freak). Hotels like Ritz Carlton provides turndown service; empty the bin, prep the bed for sleep, darken the room, put a glass and mineral water and chocolates (depending on the hotel; it could be brownies too) on the side table. A habit I have; leave my wet towel anywhere in the room, call for turndown service and step out for dinner. I'll return in less than 2 hours and see if the room is ready. I did the exact same practice today and returned in 80 minutes. My room was perfectly done, they prepped the correct bed without me saying anything, (yes, I only sleep at a specific bed if it's twin sharing), they picked up my wet towel and hang a fresh set and clean up the shower cubicle. I'm happy and settled for the night. Alhamdulilah. :: #TheRitzCarltonMillenia #RCmemories #GrandKallang #theNDPweekend #Singapoliday

Step back in time to about 50 years ago, where STB was Singapore Telephone Board, biscuits in glass jars are sold by weight and operates on a trust system. David runs this amazing immersive time capsule (private heritage gallery) and is available to share his stories by appointment with a nominal fee of $5 (and we got eyeglass candy + drink too) Just DM/WhatsApp him @weescollection 

The items are also available for rent and 70s/80s folks can purchase your fave childhood games for your children to play! #sglgexperience #sgheritage

Wherever you go, no matter what the weather, always bring your own Sunshine 😎

The Marigold is said to have derived its name from “Mary’s Gold”, taken from the fact that early Christians placed flowers instead of coins on Mary’s altar as an offering. This flower is often used in festivities honoring Mary.

The marigold is likewise associated with the sun - being vibrant yellow and gold in color. The flowers are open when the sun is out. The marigold is also called the “herb of the sun”, representing passion and even creativity.

It is also said that marigolds symbolize cruelty, grief and jealousy. It can mean to show strong passion, being associated with the legendary brave and courageous lion. Its Victorian meaning, desire for riches, is probably consequent to the legends of the flower being Mary’s gold, depicting coins.

As they are luminous and beautiful to see, they are often used as love charms. They are mostly used in weddings depicting beauty and a sign of new beginning for the married couple.

[Post 3] Another sunset at Marina Bay. The spiky structure at the right is the Esplanade Concert Hall & Theatre, nicknamed the Durian. Durian is a tropical fruit with spiky shell. It's very much sought after by locals during the the peak season around June to July. It has a unique aroma, you either love it or hate it. Durian is one of my favourite fruits. I used to be able to pick and eat freely at my family orchard but now I have to pay to enjoy it. This box of durian costs around S$50 or S$20/kg. You have to pay for the weigh of the spiky shells also even though you can't eat them. The spiky structure at Esplanade at least has the functions of letting light into the foyer areas while keeping the heat out.  #marinabaysingapore #sunsets #singapoliday #visitsingapore #exploresingapore #esplanade

.
.
.
.
The word Bharata is a mnemonic, consisting of "bha"–"ra"–"ta". According to a belief, bha stands for bhava (feelings, emotions), ra stands for raga (melody, framework for musical notes), and ta stands for tala (rhythm). The term Natya is a Sanskrit word for "dance".

:: How does it feel like to have a staycation during Covid19? From experience with Fairmont, they limit coming by to your room, they try not to provide "turn down" service unless you really want them to and they only wheel your in-room dining up to the foyer. My reservation comes with $100 worth of dining credits to be used at any of their restaurants. As none are halal certified, their dining specialist team has given me the indulgence to use the $100 for in-room dining. Fyi, they have a halal kitchen and everything on their in-room dining menu is halal. Any items delivered to your room are cling wrapped, especially food. You have to unwrap everything and even set up your own table i.e. taking out the food from the warmer beneath the table. I've seen how butlers set up tables in the suite or villa that I've stayed at and so, that experience comes in handy 😂 Voila, lunch was served at 2pm. I don't mind paying but I must like the service that I'm paying for. I'm not impressed with some of the 5-star hotels that I've stayed at before but thank you, Fairmont Singapore for the top-notch service; from check-in right up to in-room service. You're worth my every penny. I'll definitely be back ❤ :: #lunch #thestaycationweekend #FairmontSingapore #Singapoliday

Went off social media most of this year, since start of Covid-19. Especially Instagram. And even Facebook and Twitter last 1.5 months. Just not feeling it you know?

Still doesn't mean I don't occasionally get out of bed and house to check out sunsets and sunrises, blue cloud filled days, and the gorgeous lights we've been having last few weeks. The sunrays around pre and post sunrise 🌅 and sunset 🌇 have been lovely. So, lots of pictures in my phone which I stare at occasionally, having had no voice or energy to post. Just not feeling it you know?

Today, staying in because of the rain, listening to music, watching YT videos, reading, a great chilled out day, I stumbled back into IG. Inspired by some photos I saw, I'm posting this from last week or so. After the sun had set, great sunbeams across the whole sky. Beautiful sunsets and sunrises never fails to make me feel better.

Malam sabtu macam gini, Cik nak pesan sikit la that as Muslims, we must always remember our role in society. As our country continues to progress and prosper, we need to remember to help one another and not leave others behind. Ada banyak yang cannot keep up, especially the elderlies and those who have special needs. We are the heart and soul of the country and we have a part to play in building our country and steering it towards an equitable and just home for everyone. ❤️

Alhamdulillah, Zakat has enabled and will continue to enable a vibrant Muslim ecosystem in Singapore, all thanks to your contribution adik-adik every year. So, let's continue to fulfil our obligation, educate anak-anak cucu-cicit kita on their future obligation, and to encourage one another to be socially responsible in building a stronger and more compassionate Muslim society, InsyaAllah. 😊❤️

#SingapoRediscovers journey sans the vouchers checking out the historical constitutional documents and oil paintings of Singapore.

I saw the treaty letter in 1819, the surrender document, the proclamation of merger with federation of Malaya, the draft letter to separate and our proclamation of independence. The latter gave me the damn chills.

At the Siapa Namu Kamu exhibition, especially love the National Language Class painting and how it defined the sign of the times when nationalism was strong and there was a collective desire among our parents and grandparents to forge a national identity. #nationalgallery #singapoliday #art #culture #museum #singaporediscovers #singapoliday

Weekend chill vibes at The Summerhouse and Wildseed Cafe. Get to wine and dine in a charming estate surrounded by lush gardens where time just seems to fly by. Definitely one of the few places in Singapore where you'll feel like you're on vacation away from it all. And yes, you can dine in the garden dome as well! How's that for special.

View from ground level of the HSBC Rain Vortex, which is a centrepiece of the Jewel Changi Airport. It is the tallest indoor waterfall in the world, cascading 40 metres into a huge round basin that collects over 30,000 litres of waters. This area is surrounded by trees and plants that creates an extraordinary mix of nature and futuristic ambience.

post_caption:
🦞Luke’s Lobster is the dream came true of many who ate it in Japan. This Singapore branch somewhat fared less positively though. Lobster roll is still their highlight and definitely the best out of the 3 types available. 

Though the meat is fresh  and tasted sweet with the generously buttered and toasted bun, the price tag of $30 (if you dine in and pay 17% extra) and the amount of meat given does not seem like it is worth. Also the overpriced clam chowder is not recommended. Silver lining? The wait is not that long, and there’s a separate takeaway queue.

 I picked up this very well done and attractive @sunteccity brochure that was printed in March. I'm not going to show you the rest of the v nice pages inside, why not take a trip to Suntec to take it.
In a way it's poignant that I'm now using it as a Singaporean to view Singapore with fresh eyes during #covid19 and take a 'Singapoliday'. I'm not sure whether it was designed pre or post COVID-19. Or reprinted?

Throwback Thursdays - Revisitng Singapore's Beautiful Spots

Hope everyone read the news that the @visit_singapore ,Singapore Tourism Board (STB) has launched a S$45 million marketing campaign over the next 9 months to promote the local travels & staycations also shortly dubbed as #singapoliday.

Yay!! We can take a staycation now and relax in the local hotels. Hygiene levels have been ramped up and the residents would have a lot of value for money experiences, packages and promos. 

To celebrate Singapore 🇸🇬 and its beauty, here is a throwback to a quick trip I took to Haji lane in the year 2015. Haji lane is home to an array of small cafes, boutiques and shop houses. The lane looks so colourful with its wall paintings and is quite an unique experience as opposed to Singapore's bustling other tourist spots.

🇸🇬: Breakfast at Fullerton Hotel! 

2 eggs done sunny side up, over a sourdough bread with hashbrowns, baked beans, tomatoes, bacon and sausage.

Buttermilk pancakes, with a Berry compote, maple syrup, whipped cream and bacon. 

With phase 2 currently in effect. Most hotels are offering an ala carte buffet menu with only a few main items. At the fullerton there were only 5! There wasn't any offering of cheese or cereal, and only a minimal bread basket. 

Now heres the tip... you can actually ask for anything you might normally find in a 5 star Hotel breakfast! Like a cheese board, cereal, fruits... but maybe not something you'd normally not find on a buffet breakfast spread like pizza or steak :(

Loving the Ann Siang / Duxton / Telok Ayer area very much these days. There’re quaint conservation shophouses, glorified and understated eats - Michelin to Maxwell - REALLY nice/chic bars, (views of) towering skyscrapers, and little surprises featuring anything from heritage and hidden posh boutique hotels to a dedicated london-esque men’s shaving supplies store. 

The hubs and I like taking long walks around the alleyways until we stumble upon something - and yesterday we found this lovely rooftop bar at @screening_room, offering great views of Ann Siang’s splendid intertextuality. Just a huge pity that it’s closing on Weds!

Let’s #Singapoliday and #singaporediscovers interesting places to visit with your family!!

We highly encourage a staycation at Government approved hotel. Staycation had been one of our TOP 1 favourite. Of all the 3 times we visited over these 6months, we seen improvement over improvement on the health protocol, great to know that the government agency and hotel are keeping our family safe. For this time, our choice of hotel had to be the one with swimming pool and waterplay for sure. It helps to keep adult and children occupied.

Shangri-La Hotel tick all the boxes for us. With the Playcation package we get to have alacarte breakfast at The Line, picnic basket, 100 bucks f&b credit per night, as well as freepass for The Buds indoor playground and The Splash Zone.

There’s many more activities for kids to do there!! (View last slide for the sample of activity that we had and the kiddo carepack).

Look at the kids smiling and laughing happily, we are glad that we ReDiscoverSingapore again. 

What should we do next??

#staycation #phase2reopening #phase2 #sgunited #supportlocal #shangrilahotel #familytime #familyfriendly #familyfriendlyhotel #kidsfriendlyhotel #sghotel @shangrilasg #sgmom #sgkids #sgstaycation #staycation #kidsfriendly #sgbaby

Push on, Singapore! 🇸🇬

Ytd, my fambam went to Gardens By The Bay to visit Flower Dome and Cloud Forest. While we were not expecting throngs of visitors due to CoVid19, it was shocking to see absolutely no queue at either attractions.

When we were inside, we had ample of space. There was no need to even demarcate social distancing for phototaking at various checkpoints. The impact from CoVid19 was plain to see and how dependent our nation is on tourism is scary. As a country, we are not able to self-drive from our nation’s consumption. We need visitors. We need Singapore to open up. And we need it fast. I can’t imagine how ravaged our economy will be if CoVid19 stays through 2021. I can only hope.

On the bright side, there’s no better time to visit all these attractions! Let’s bring our family out to have some fun and enjoy the beautiful country we call home! 💪🏻💪🏻

Traditional Chinese opera, was introduced to Singapore by Chinese immigrants who arrived in the latter half of the 19th century. These Chinese immigrants later built temples for worship, and opera would be staged outdoors on the temple grounds for the amusement of deities and as a form of respect during the celebration of deities’ birthdays and customary festivals. Such performances were probably free to watch, as the opera troupes were engaged and paid for by businessmen or temples and associations.⁠
.
Wayang has survived modernisation and continues to be performed in Singapore. This is due to efforts by the government and various community associations to preserve and promote it as part of Singapore’s cultural heritage as well as the resurgence of performances by troupes from China and the revival of local amateur troupes.⁠
.⁠
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg⁠
